{"title_page": "Little black dress", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Little Black Dress (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Anneke Gr\u00f6nloh 1964 Eurovision dress.jpg|thumb|A little black dress from 1964]]\n\nA '''little black dress''' ('''LBD''') is a black [[evening gown|evening]] or [[cocktail dress]], cut simply and often quite short. [[History of fashion design|Fashion historians]] ascribe the origins of the little black dress to the 1920s designs of [[Coco Chanel]] and [[Jean Patou]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Steele|first=Valerie|title=Paris Fashion: A Cultural History|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1988|pages=[https://archive.org/details/parisfashioncult0000stee/page/246 246\u2013248]|isbn=0-19-504465-7|url=https://archive.org/details/parisfashioncult0000stee/page/246}}</ref> intended to be long-lasting, versatile, affordable, accessible to the widest market possible and in a neutral colour. Its ubiquity is such that it is often simply referred to as the \"LBD\".<ref>{{cite web|author=styledotcom |url=http://www.style.com/stylefile/2010/08/the-lbd-gets-official/ |title=The LBD Gets Official |work=Style.com |date=2010-08-19 |accessdate=2013-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/04/15/katy-perry-looks-stunning-in-slinky-lbd-115875-22187069/ |title=Katy Perry looks stunning in slinky LBD |work=Mirror.co.uk |date=2010-04-15 |accessdate=2013-07-13}}</ref><ref>[http://www.niu.edu/PubAffairs/RELEASES/2007/feb/blackdress.shtml ''\"Women\u2019s History Month kicks off in \u2018Little Black Dress\u2019 style\"'', Northern Illinois University] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011134843/http://niu.edu/PubAffairs/RELEASES/2007/feb/blackdress.shtml |date=2010-10-11 }}</ref> \n[[File:Klein_zwart_jurkje.JPG|thumb|Variations on Chanel's little black dress during the Chanel: The Legend exhibition at the Gemeentemuseum in The Hague.]]\nThe \"little black dress\" is considered essential to a complete [[Clothing|wardrobe]] by many women and fashion observers, who believe it a \"rule of fashion\" that every woman should own a simple, elegant black dress that can be dressed up or down depending on the occasion: for example, worn with a jacket and pumps for daytime business wear or with more ornate jewelry and accessories for evening or a formal event such as a [[wedding]] or a [[ball (dance party)|ball]].\n\n==History==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2017}}\nBlack has always been [[Black#Associations_and_symbolism|a color rich in symbolism]]. In the early 16th century, black represented wealth among Spanish Aristocrats and Dutch merchants as it was incredibly expensive to produce the black color from \"imported oak apples.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/10/the-underclass-origins-of-the-little-black-dress/542910/|title=The Underclass Origins of the Little Black Dress|last=Puhak|first=Shelley|date=2017-10-13|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> In the early 18th century, black represented romance and artistry. As [[Ann Demeulemeester]] said of it, \"Black is poetic. How do you imagine a poet? In a bright yellow jacket? Probably not.\" In the early 19th century, black was adopted by the [[Romantics]] such as [[Byron]], [[Percy Bysshe Shelley|Shelley]], and [[Keats]], due ton its melancholic aura. As the [[Victorian era]] began, black transitions from a color of art to one of grief and mourning \u2013 widows were expected to wear black for at least four years \u2013 and also for service livery, as the uniform for [[maid]]s.\n\nIn 1926 [[Gabrielle Chanel|Gabrielle \"Coco\" Chanel]] published a picture of a short, simple black dress in American ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''. It was calf-length, straight and decorated only by a few diagonal lines. ''Vogue'' called it \"Chanel's Ford\". Like the [[Model T]], the little black dress was simple and accessible for women of all social classes. ''Vogue'' also said that the LBD would become \"a sort of uniform for all women of taste\".<ref name=\"Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). The Little Black Dress. Aurum.\"/> This, as well as other designs by the house of Chanel helped disassociate black from mourning, and reinvent it as the uniform of the high-class, wealthy, and chic. As Coco herself proclaimed, \"I imposed black; it's still going strong today, for black wipes out everything else around.\"<ref name=picardie92>{{Cite book|title=Coco Chanel: the legend and the life |last=Picardie |first=Justine |publisher=Harper Collins Publishers|year=2010|isbn=9780061963858|location=London|pages=92\u201393}}</ref>\n\nThe little black dress continued to be popular through the [[Great Depression]], predominantly through its economy and elegance, albeit with the line lengthened somewhat. [[Hollywood]]'s influence on fashion helped the little black dress's popularity, but for more practical reasons: as [[Technicolor]] films became more common, filmmakers relied on little black dresses because other colors looked distorted on screen and botched the coloring process. During [[World War II]], the style continued in part due to widespread rationing of textiles, and in part as a common uniform (accessorized for businesswear) for civilian women entering the workforce.\n[[File:Black evening dress by Patou.jpg|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Black evening dress by Jean Patou]]\nThe rise of [[The New Look (style)|Dior's \"New Look\"]] in the post-war era and the sexual conservatism of the 1950s returned the little black dress to its roots as a uniform and a symbol of the dangerous woman. Hollywood [[femme fatale]]s and [[fallen women]] characters were portrayed often in black halter-style dresses in contrast to the more conservative dresses of housewives or more wholesome Hollywood stars. Synthetic fibres made popular in the 1940s and 1950s broadened the availability and affordability of many designs.\n\nThe generation gap of the 1960s created a dichotomy in the design of the little black dress. The younger \"[[mod (subculture)|mod]]\" generation preferred, in general, a miniskirt on their versions of the dress and designers catering to the [[youth culture]] continued to push the envelope - shortening the skirt even more, creating cutouts or slits in the skirt or bodice of the dress, using sheer fabrics such as [[netting]] or [[Tulle (netting)|tulle]]. Many women aspired to simple black sheath dresses similar to the [[Black Givenchy dress of Audrey Hepburn|black Givenchy dress]] worn by [[Audrey Hepburn]] in the film ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]''.\n\nThe popularity of casual fabrics, especially knits, for dress and business wear during the 1980s brought the little black dress back into vogue. Coupled with the fitness craze, the new designs incorporated details already popular at the time such as broad shoulders or [[Overskirt|peplums]]: later in the decade and into the 1990s, simpler designs in a variety of lengths and fullness were popular. The [[Grunge#Presentation and fashion|grunge]] culture of the 1990s saw the combination of the little black dress with both sandals and [[combat boots]], though the dress itself remained simple in cut and fabric.\n\nThe new glamour of the late 1990s led to new variations of the dress but, like the 1950s and the 1970s, colour re-emerged as a factor in fashion and formalwear and repeatedly shows an aversion to black. The resurgence of body conscious clothing, muted colour schemes, and the reemergence of predominant black, along with the retrospective trends of the 1980s in the late 2000s paved way to the return of interest to the dress.\n\n==Famous little black dresses==\n\nThe [[black Givenchy dress of Audrey Hepburn]] as Holly Golightly in ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany\u2019s]]'', designed by [[Hubert de Givenchy]], epitomized the standard for wearing little black dresses accessorized with pearls (together called \"basic black\"), as was frequently seen throughout the early 1960s. The dress set a record in 2006 when it was auctioned for \u00a3410,000, six times its original estimate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2006/12/06/audrey-hepburn-dress/ |title=Audrey Hepburn's Little Black Dress Sells for a Fortune |work=Hellomagazine.com |date=2006-12-06 |accessdate=2013-07-13}}</ref>\n\n[[Betty Boop]], a cartoon character based in part on the 1920s \"[[it girl]]\" [[Clara Bow]], was drawn wearing a little black dress in her early films, though with [[Technicolor]] later, Betty's dress became red.<ref name=\"Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). The Little Black Dress. Aurum.\">Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). ''The Little Black Dress''. Aurum.</ref> \n[[File:Betty_Boop_patent_fig1.jpg|thumb|Betty Boop by Max Fleischer, 1931]]\n\n[[Wallis Simpson]], Duchess of Windsor, was known to own several little black dresses and said much in praise of the garments. One quote of the Duchess: \"When a little black dress is right, there is nothing else to wear in its place.\"<ref name=\"Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). The Little Black Dress. Aurum.\"/>\n\n[[Edith Piaf]], the French folk icon, performed in a black sheath dress throughout her career: for this habit she was nicknamed \"little black sparrow\". It was thought that the dress helped audiences focus more on Piaf's singing and less on her appearance.<ref name=\"Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). The Little Black Dress. Aurum.\"/>\n\n[[Diana, Princess of Wales]] wore a black Christina Stambolian dress while at Serpentine Gallery\u2019s summer party, hosted by Vanity Fair in June 1994, the night [[Charles, Prince of Wales]] admitted he had an adulterous relationship with [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Camilla]], [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Duchess of Cornwall]]. Diana's dress has been compared to a \"little black dress\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/princess-diana-revenge-dress_us_5b3514a2e4b0b5e692f5cf6b|title=The Day Princess Diana And Her 'Revenge Dress' Shocked The World}}</ref>\n\nIn an incident at [[London]]'s [[Covent Garden]] theatre in 2004, a director fired the then-[[obseity|obese]] [[soprano]] [[Deborah Voigt]] from an [[opera]] because she could not fit into a \"little black cocktail dress\", replacing her with the slimmer [[Anne Schwanewilms]].<ref name=Body>Anthony Tommasini, \"With Surgery, Soprano Sheds a Br\u00fcnnhilde Body,\" ''New York Times'', March 27, 2005, found at [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/27/arts/music/27voig.html New York Times website]. ''Before and after images included''. Accessed May 27, 2009.</ref><ref name=Date>Anthony Tommasini, \"Second Date With a Little Black Dress,\" ''New York Times'', June 11, 2008, found at [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/11/arts/music/11voig.html New York Times website]. Accessed May 27, 2009.</ref><ref name=Heft>Vivien Schweitzer, \"Music Review: A Slimmed-Down Diva Keeps Her Vocal Heft,\" ''New York Times'', June 18, 2009, found at [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/18/arts/music/18aria.html New York Times website]. Accessed May 27, 2009.</ref><ref name=\"cbs\">\"Deborah Voigt: Off The Scales: Opera Star Talks About Lifelong Battle With Weight,\" found at [http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/01/27/60minutes/main1245332.shtml \"Deborah Voigt: Off The Scales, Opera Star Talks About Lifelong Battle With Weight\"], CBS News. Retrieved May 29, 2009.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal-inline|Fashion}}\n{{Commons Category|Little black dresses}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). ''The Little Black Dress''. Aurum. {{ISBN|1-85410-604-X}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121108143616/http://fashion.about.com/cs/dresses/a/littleblackdres.htm \"Little Black Dress Transcends Fashion\"]. About.com. May 2006\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150905110551/http://www.fiftiesweb.com/fashion/basic-black-dress.htm \u201cSixties Fashions\u201d]. June 2, 2006.\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/womanshour/04/2006_12_thu.shtml \"The Little Black Dress\"]. ''Woman\u2019s Hour Radio''.  [[BBC]]. May 2006.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170630024437/http://www.fashionculte.com/fashion/little-black-dress-myth/ \"The Myth Of The Little Black Dress\"]. ''Jane Curtain'' . The Fashion Culte Magazine. November 2014.\n\n{{Chanel}}\n{{Clothing}}\n\n[[Category:1920s fashion]]\n[[Category:20th-century fashion]]\n[[Category:21st-century fashion]]\n[[Category:Dresses]]\n[[Category:History of clothing (Western fashion)]]\n[[Category:History of fashion]]\n[[Category:Chanel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Little Black Dress (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Anneke Gr\u00f6nloh 1964 Eurovision dress.jpg|thumb|A little black dress from 1964]]\n\nA '''little black dress''' ('''LBD''') is a black [[evening gown|evening]] or [[cocktail dress]], cut simply and often quite short. [[History of fashion design|Fashion historians]] ascribe the origins of the little black dress to the 1920s designs of [[Coco Chanel]] and [[Jean Patou]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Steele|first=Valerie|title=Paris Fashion: A Cultural History|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1988|pages=[https://archive.org/details/parisfashioncult0000stee/page/246 246\u2013248]|isbn=0-19-504465-7|url=https://archive.org/details/parisfashioncult0000stee/page/246}}</ref> intended to be long-lasting, versatile, affordable, accessible to the widest market possible and in a neutral colour. Its ubiquity is such that it is often simply referred to as the \"LBD\".<ref>{{cite web|author=styledotcom |url=http://www.style.com/stylefile/2010/08/the-lbd-gets-official/ |title=The LBD Gets Official |work=Style.com |date=2010-08-19 |accessdate=2013-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/04/15/katy-perry-looks-stunning-in-slinky-lbd-115875-22187069/ |title=Katy Perry looks stunning in slinky LBD |work=Mirror.co.uk |date=2010-04-15 |accessdate=2013-07-13}}</ref><ref>[http://www.niu.edu/PubAffairs/RELEASES/2007/feb/blackdress.shtml ''\"Women\u2019s History Month kicks off in \u2018Little Black Dress\u2019 style\"'', Northern Illinois University] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011134843/http://niu.edu/PubAffairs/RELEASES/2007/feb/blackdress.shtml |date=2010-10-11 }}</ref> \n[[File:Klein_zwart_jurkje.JPG|thumb|Variations on Chanel's little black dress during the Chanel: The Legend exhibition at the Gemeentemuseum in The Hague.]]\nThe \"little black dress\" is considered essential to a complete [[Clothing|wardrobe]] by many women and fashion observers, who believe it a \"rule of fashion\" that every woman should own a simple, elegant black dress that can be dressed up or down depending on the occasion: for example, worn with a jacket and pumps for daytime business wear or with more ornate jewelry and accessories for evening or a formal event such as a [[wedding]] or a [[ball (dance party)|ball]].\n\n==History==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2017}}\nBlack has always been [[Black#Associations_and_symbolism|a color rich in symbolism]]. In the early 16th century, black represented wealth among Spanish Aristocrats and Dutch merchants as it was incredibly expensive to produce the black color from \"imported oak apples.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/10/the-underclass-origins-of-the-little-black-dress/542910/|title=The Underclass Origins of the Little Black Dress|last=Puhak|first=Shelley|date=2017-10-13|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> In the early 18th century, black represented romance and artistry. As [[Ann Demeulemeester]] said of it, \"Black is poetic. How do you imagine a poet? In a bright yellow jacket? Probably not.\" In the early 19th century, black was adopted by the [[Romantics]] such as [[Byron]], [[Percy Bysshe Shelley|Shelley]], and [[Keats]], due to its melancholic aura. As the [[Victorian era]] began, black transitions from a color of art to one of grief and mourning \u2013 widows were expected to wear black for at least four years \u2013 and also for service livery, as the uniform for [[maid]]s.\n\nIn 1926 [[Gabrielle Chanel|Gabrielle \"Coco\" Chanel]] published a picture of a short, simple black dress in American ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''. It was calf-length, straight and decorated only by a few diagonal lines. ''Vogue'' called it \"Chanel's Ford\". Like the [[Model T]], the little black dress was simple and accessible for women of all social classes. ''Vogue'' also said that the LBD would become \"a sort of uniform for all women of taste\".<ref name=\"Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). The Little Black Dress. Aurum.\"/> This, as well as other designs by the house of Chanel helped disassociate black from mourning, and reinvent it as the uniform of the high-class, wealthy, and chic. As Coco herself proclaimed, \"I imposed black; it's still going strong today, for black wipes out everything else around.\"<ref name=picardie92>{{Cite book|title=Coco Chanel: the legend and the life |last=Picardie |first=Justine |publisher=Harper Collins Publishers|year=2010|isbn=9780061963858|location=London|pages=92\u201393}}</ref>\n\nThe little black dress continued to be popular through the [[Great Depression]], predominantly through its economy and elegance, albeit with the line lengthened somewhat. [[Hollywood]]'s influence on fashion helped the little black dress's popularity, but for more practical reasons: as [[Technicolor]] films became more common, filmmakers relied on little black dresses because other colors looked distorted on screen and botched the coloring process. During [[World War II]], the style continued in part due to widespread rationing of textiles, and in part as a common uniform (accessorized for businesswear) for civilian women entering the workforce.\n[[File:Black evening dress by Patou.jpg|alt=|thumb|300x300px|Black evening dress by Jean Patou]]\nThe rise of [[The New Look (style)|Dior's \"New Look\"]] in the post-war era and the sexual conservatism of the 1950s returned the little black dress to its roots as a uniform and a symbol of the dangerous woman. Hollywood [[femme fatale]]s and [[fallen women]] characters were portrayed often in black halter-style dresses in contrast to the more conservative dresses of housewives or more wholesome Hollywood stars. Synthetic fibres made popular in the 1940s and 1950s broadened the availability and affordability of many designs.\n\nThe generation gap of the 1960s created a dichotomy in the design of the little black dress. The younger \"[[mod (subculture)|mod]]\" generation preferred, in general, a miniskirt on their versions of the dress and designers catering to the [[youth culture]] continued to push the envelope - shortening the skirt even more, creating cutouts or slits in the skirt or bodice of the dress, using sheer fabrics such as [[netting]] or [[Tulle (netting)|tulle]]. Many women aspired to simple black sheath dresses similar to the [[Black Givenchy dress of Audrey Hepburn|black Givenchy dress]] worn by [[Audrey Hepburn]] in the film ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]''.\n\nThe popularity of casual fabrics, especially knits, for dress and business wear during the 1980s brought the little black dress back into vogue. Coupled with the fitness craze, the new designs incorporated details already popular at the time such as broad shoulders or [[Overskirt|peplums]]: later in the decade and into the 1990s, simpler designs in a variety of lengths and fullness were popular. The [[Grunge#Presentation and fashion|grunge]] culture of the 1990s saw the combination of the little black dress with both sandals and [[combat boots]], though the dress itself remained simple in cut and fabric.\n\nThe new glamour of the late 1990s led to new variations of the dress but, like the 1950s and the 1970s, colour re-emerged as a factor in fashion and formalwear and repeatedly shows an aversion to black. The resurgence of body conscious clothing, muted colour schemes, and the reemergence of predominant black, along with the retrospective trends of the 1980s in the late 2000s paved way to the return of interest to the dress.\n\n==Famous little black dresses==\n\nThe [[black Givenchy dress of Audrey Hepburn]] as Holly Golightly in ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany\u2019s]]'', designed by [[Hubert de Givenchy]], epitomized the standard for wearing little black dresses accessorized with pearls (together called \"basic black\"), as was frequently seen throughout the early 1960s. The dress set a record in 2006 when it was auctioned for \u00a3410,000, six times its original estimate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2006/12/06/audrey-hepburn-dress/ |title=Audrey Hepburn's Little Black Dress Sells for a Fortune |work=Hellomagazine.com |date=2006-12-06 |accessdate=2013-07-13}}</ref>\n\n[[Betty Boop]], a cartoon character based in part on the 1920s \"[[it girl]]\" [[Clara Bow]], was drawn wearing a little black dress in her early films, though with [[Technicolor]] later, Betty's dress became red.<ref name=\"Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). The Little Black Dress. Aurum.\">Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). ''The Little Black Dress''. Aurum.</ref> \n[[File:Betty_Boop_patent_fig1.jpg|thumb|Betty Boop by Max Fleischer, 1931]]\n\n[[Wallis Simpson]], Duchess of Windsor, was known to own several little black dresses and said much in praise of the garments. One quote of the Duchess: \"When a little black dress is right, there is nothing else to wear in its place.\"<ref name=\"Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). The Little Black Dress. Aurum.\"/>\n\n[[Edith Piaf]], the French folk icon, performed in a black sheath dress throughout her career: for this habit she was nicknamed \"little black sparrow\". It was thought that the dress helped audiences focus more on Piaf's singing and less on her appearance.<ref name=\"Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). The Little Black Dress. Aurum.\"/>\n\n[[Diana, Princess of Wales]] wore a black Christina Stambolian dress while at Serpentine Gallery\u2019s summer party, hosted by Vanity Fair in June 1994, the night [[Charles, Prince of Wales]] admitted he had an adulterous relationship with [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Camilla]], [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Duchess of Cornwall]]. Diana's dress has been compared to a \"little black dress\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/princess-diana-revenge-dress_us_5b3514a2e4b0b5e692f5cf6b|title=The Day Princess Diana And Her 'Revenge Dress' Shocked The World}}</ref>\n\nIn an incident at [[London]]'s [[Covent Garden]] theatre in 2004, a director fired the then-[[obseity|obese]] [[soprano]] [[Deborah Voigt]] from an [[opera]] because she could not fit into a \"little black cocktail dress\", replacing her with the slimmer [[Anne Schwanewilms]].<ref name=Body>Anthony Tommasini, \"With Surgery, Soprano Sheds a Br\u00fcnnhilde Body,\" ''New York Times'', March 27, 2005, found at [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/27/arts/music/27voig.html New York Times website]. ''Before and after images included''. Accessed May 27, 2009.</ref><ref name=Date>Anthony Tommasini, \"Second Date With a Little Black Dress,\" ''New York Times'', June 11, 2008, found at [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/11/arts/music/11voig.html New York Times website]. Accessed May 27, 2009.</ref><ref name=Heft>Vivien Schweitzer, \"Music Review: A Slimmed-Down Diva Keeps Her Vocal Heft,\" ''New York Times'', June 18, 2009, found at [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/18/arts/music/18aria.html New York Times website]. Accessed May 27, 2009.</ref><ref name=\"cbs\">\"Deborah Voigt: Off The Scales: Opera Star Talks About Lifelong Battle With Weight,\" found at [http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/01/27/60minutes/main1245332.shtml \"Deborah Voigt: Off The Scales, Opera Star Talks About Lifelong Battle With Weight\"], CBS News. Retrieved May 29, 2009.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal-inline|Fashion}}\n{{Commons Category|Little black dresses}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Edelman, Amy Holman (1998). ''The Little Black Dress''. Aurum. {{ISBN|1-85410-604-X}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121108143616/http://fashion.about.com/cs/dresses/a/littleblackdres.htm \"Little Black Dress Transcends Fashion\"]. About.com. May 2006\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150905110551/http://www.fiftiesweb.com/fashion/basic-black-dress.htm \u201cSixties Fashions\u201d]. June 2, 2006.\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/womanshour/04/2006_12_thu.shtml \"The Little Black Dress\"]. ''Woman\u2019s Hour Radio''.  [[BBC]]. May 2006.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170630024437/http://www.fashionculte.com/fashion/little-black-dress-myth/ \"The Myth Of The Little Black Dress\"]. ''Jane Curtain'' . The Fashion Culte Magazine. November 2014.\n\n{{Chanel}}\n{{Clothing}}\n\n[[Category:1920s fashion]]\n[[Category:20th-century fashion]]\n[[Category:21st-century fashion]]\n[[Category:Dresses]]\n[[Category:History of clothing (Western fashion)]]\n[[Category:History of fashion]]\n[[Category:Chanel]]\n", "name_user": "47.225.12.225", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_black_dress"}
{"title_page": "Be the Creature", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Be the Creature\n| image              =\n| caption            =\n| genre              = [[Documentary film|Documentary]]\n| creator            = Chris Kratt, Martin Kratt\n| presenter          = [[Martin Kratt]]<br>[[Chris Kratt]]\n| country            = United States<br>Canada\n| language           = English, French\n| num_seasons        = 3\n| num_episodes       = 30\n| executive_producer = Chris Kratt, Martin Kratt\n| producer           = Chris Kratt, Martin Kratt \n| director           = Chris Kratt, Martin Kratt \n| runtime            = 42 minutes\n| company = [[Decode Entertainment]]<br>Kratt Brothers Company Limited\n| network            = [[National Geographic Channel]], [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]\n| first_aired        = October 5, 2003\n| last_aired         = April 9, 2004\n| website            = https://web.archive.org/web/20050823090705/http://www.bethecreature.tv:80/\n}}\n'''''Be the Creature''''' is a creation of the Kratt Brothers ([[Chris Kratt|Chris]] and [[Martin Kratt|Martin]]). A wildlife series designed to immerse both the brothers and the viewers in the world of animals, unlike the brothers' previous works, ''[[Kratts' Creatures]]'' and ''[[Zoboomafoo]]'', ''Be the Creature'' is oriented towards teens and adults. The brothers place themselves in the thick of the animal world, sometimes in high-intensity or dangerous situations. The series also features some graphic footage in an effort to portray life in the wild truthfully.\n\nA second season entitled, ''Be the Creature 2'', began in 2005. The show is airing on [[National Geographic Wild]].\nA third season entitled, \" Be The Creature 3\", began in 2007.\n\n==List of episodes==\n\n===Season 1===\n# Brown Bear\n# African Wild Dog\n# African Lion\n# Japanese Macaque\n# Lemur\n# Manatee\n# Coastal Creature\n# Chimpanzee\n# Banded Mongoose\n# Mexican Free-Tailed Bat\n# Great White Shark\n# Gelada Baboon\n# Eastern Gray Kangaroo\n\n===Season 2===\n# Cheetah\n# Orangutan\n# Komodo Dragon\n# Meerkat\n# Kill Zone\n# The Pantanal\n# Galapagos\n# Spotted Hyena\n# Battling Bighorn\n# Staying Alive\n# Weapons For Survival\n# Leopard\n# Ethiopian Wolf\n# Leopard\n# Expedition Leopard\n# Expedition Japanese Macaque\n\n===Season 3===\n# Giant Panda\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050823090705/http://www.bethecreature.tv/ ''Be the Creature'' Official Site]\n*[http://www.krattbrothers.com The Kratt Brothers Official Site]\n\n==Sources==\n*[http://www.tv.com/shows/be-the-creature/episodes/]\n\n{{The Kratt Brothers}}\n{{National Geographic TV}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Be The Creature}}\n[[Category:American non-fiction television series]]\n[[Category:Nature educational television series]]\n[[Category:Television series about brothers]]\n[[Category:National Geographic Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by DHX Media]]\n[[Category:American television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Chris Kratt]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Martin Kratt]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Be the Creature\n| image              =\n| caption            =\n| genre              = [[Documentary film|Documentary]]\n| creator            = Chris Kratt, Martin Kratt\n| presenter          = [[Martin Kratt]]<br>[[Chris Kratt]]\n| country            = United States<br>Canada\n| language           = English, French\n| num_seasons        = 3\n| num_episodes       = 30\n| executive_producer = Chris Kratt, Martin Kratt\n| producer           = Chris Kratt, Martin Kratt \n| director           = Chris Kratt, Martin Kratt \n| runtime            = 42 minutes\n| company = [[Decode Entertainment]]<br>Kratt Brothers Company Limited\n| network            = [[National Geographic Channel]], [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]\n| first_air